        "### Q&A\n",
        "\n",
        "**What was the objective of this data analysis task?**\n",
        "The objective was to preprocess the Titanic dataset (cleaning, feature engineering, scaling, and encoding) and train a classification model to predict passenger survival, followed by a detailed performance evaluation.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Which model was used and how did it perform?**\n",
        "A **Logistic Regression** model (using the `liblinear` solver) was trained. It achieved an **Accuracy of 81.53%**, a **Precision of 82.26%**, and an **F1-Score of 77.86%** on the test set.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What were the main data preprocessing steps?**\n",
        "The workflow included handling missing values (imputing age with median and embarkation with mode), removing 107 duplicate rows, dropping the 'deck' column due to 77% missing data, creating new features like `FamilySize` and `IsAlone`, and applying both Label and One-Hot encoding to categorical variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Data Analysis Key Findings\n",
        "\n",
        "*   **Missing Data & Duplicates:** The initial dataset contained **107 duplicate rows** and significant missing values in `deck` (**77.22%**) and `age` (**19.87%**). These were addressed by dropping the `deck` column and imputing `age`.\n",
        "*   **Outlier Detection:** Statistical analysis using the IQR method identified significant outliers in the `fare` column (**13.01%** of data points) and `FamilySize` (**10.59%**).\n",
        "*   **Feature Engineering:** New predictive features were successfully derived, including `FamilySize` (ranging from 1 to 11) and `IsAlone`. Since the original Seaborn dataset lacked a 'Name' column, the `who` column was mapped to create a proxy `Title` feature.\n",
        "*   **Data Transformation:** The feature space expanded from **15 original columns to 24 final features** after One-Hot Encoding and numerical scaling (StandardScaler and MinMaxScaler).\n",
        "*   **Model Evaluation:** The Confusion Matrix revealed that the model is slightly more prone to **False Negatives** (missing actual survivors) than False Positives, though it maintains a high Precision of **82.26%**.\n",
